    3.
        One way in which Muslims celebrate Id-ul-Fitr is by prayer and silent reflection. Muslims will celebrate Id-ul-Fitr by attending prayer, commemorating the end of Ramadan.

        Another way in which Muslims celebrate Id-ul-Fitr is by attending a large celebration and gathering with other Muslims, wherein they will have a feast and eat lots of food. This celebrates the abundance which has been granted to humanity by Allah.
    4.
        One reason why the festival of Ashura is important for Shi'a Muslims is because in the Qu'ran it is recorded as the day Hussein martyred himself for the Shi'a cause. Shi'a Muslims will reflect upon his sacrifice and his role in the Islamic faith upon the festival of Ashura.

        One reason why the festival of Ashura is important for Sunni Muslims is because in the Qu'ran it is recorded as a day in which Muhammad led them in fasting in order to show their closeness to Allah. Modern Sunni Muslims will follow in Muhammad's footsteps and fast or otherwise perform actions which they believe demonstrate their spirituality.
    5.
        One reason why some Muslims might suggest fasting is the most important religious activyt during the month of Ramadna is because it is almost certainly the most prominent. In all denominations of Islam Sawm is very important, as it is part of the Five Pillars of Islam, the fundamental aspects of Islamic faith. Furthermore, there is certainly a corpus of rules around Sawm -- from penalties (donating the cost of a meal if breaking fast was accidental or unavoidable; and for many meals if the breaking was intentional), to exemptions (pregnant women, the young, the elderly, or the infirm): there is even a thriving ecosystem of digital tools to manage and navigate this set of rules. It is hard not to see why Sawm might be regarded as the most important aspect of Ramadan in the face of all this ceremony.

        Furtheremore, Sawm helps bring the Muslim closer to God. By practicing Sawm, and abstaining from food, the Muslim develops a heightened sense of connection to God, and demonstrates his or her willingness to struggle and sacrifice to obey God. In this sense, Sawm is perhaps one of the most important aspects of Ramadan. In addition, in the Qu'ran it is laid out that Sawm was commanded by God, and indeed Muhammad himself fasted in this manner. In the Qu'ran, it is also said: "Ye who believe, obey God and his Messenger". It is clear that God's word should be obeyed and is very important, so since God declared that Sawm should be practiced, it is only natural that Sawm must be regarded as the most important religious activity during the month of Ramadan.

        However, these arguments in my view do not address one key point: that it is not only the Muslim's duty to obey the word of God, but also to interpret and understand His intent and obey not only the letter of the law but also its spirit. True, Sawm brings Muslims closer to God. But, the ultimate goal of a Muslim -- to become closer to God; to be morally good and do good for others -- must not be overlooked. If instead the statement was phrased that Sawm was most commonly the best way to achieve these goals during Ramadan, and that those goals remained the most important, then I would agree wholeheartedly -- but, here I find other aspects such as peacemaking e.g. or remaining civil and polite must be emphasized still; if a Muslim keeps his fast but does not remain civil it is hard to argue he is carrying out the command of God.

        In addition, many people are unable to carry out Sawm or are exempt from it. The notion that the act of Sawm itself instead of the intentions or ideas which it represents is the most important activity during Ramadan cannot be reconciled in my view with the amount of devout Muslims which are exempt from Sawm; Allah would not have created a world wherein it would be so impossible for such a large proportion of the population to carry out the most important religous act if indeed it was the act itself that held the import. I argue instead that it is one's intent -- to sacrifice in order to appease God and to show one's faith -- that is important, not just the act itself, because otherwise many Muslims would be excluded from the faith for reasons outside their control, which we know cannot be the case, as it is one of the 99 names of Allah that he is Fair and Just.

        Hence, I do not agree with the statement. Although Sawm represents a very important aspect of Ramadan, I believe that it is the ideas and intentions behind the act of Sawm that hold the most importance, rather than the actual act itself.
